      Worldwide states and provinces from [Natural Earth](http://naturalearthdata.com).
      
      US neighborhood boundaries provided by [Zillow](http://www.zillow.com/howto/api/neighborhood-boundaries.htm) under a CC-SLA license.

      This product includes GeoLite data created by MaxMind, available from [http://www.maxmind.com/](http://www.maxmind.com/).

      The [OpenStreetMap](http://openstreetmap.org) and [PostGIS](http://postgis.refractions.net/) projects have also provided some fantastic tools.

      Using geocoding code from <a href="http://www.geoiq.com/">GeoIQ</a> and [Schuyler Erle](https://github.com/geocommons/geocoder).
      
      Uses the [Ocropus project](http://code.google.com/p/ocropus/) for OCR on images, and [catdoc](http://wagner.pp.ru/~vitus/software/catdoc/) for parsing pre-XML Word and Excel documents
      
      Uses the [Hpricot](http://hpricot.com/) library for parsing HTML.

      The [Boilerpipe](http://code.google.com/p/boilerpipe/) library is used to recognize and extract the main story text from documents.

      Uses my Ruby port of Eamon Daly and Jon Orwant's original [GenderFromName Perl module](http://search.cpan.org/~edaly/Text-GenderFromName-0.32/GenderFromName.pm) to classify first names.
  
      Uses street and place data from <a href="http://www.openstreetmap.org/">OpenStreetMap</a>

      Uses region and postal code data from <a href="http://www.geonames.org/">GeoNames</a>.

      Incorporates the city-level <a href="http://www.twofishes.net/">TwoFishes geocoder</a> written by <a href="http://twitter.com/blackmad">David Blackman</a> at Foursquare.

